La 628-E8 is a ' novel ' by the French novelist and playwright Octave Mirbeau , published by Fasquelle in 1907 .
The Little Locksmith is a memoir by Katharine Butler Hathaway about the effects of spinal tuberculosis on her childhood and adult life .
Time for Bed is a 1996 novel by David Baddiel ( ISBN 978 - 0751519785 ) .
The Devils of Loudun is a 1952 non - fiction novel by Aldous Huxley .
Mortal Engines is the first of four novels in Philip Reeve 's quartet of the same name .
A Step From Heaven is the first novel by An Na , published in 2001 by Front Street Press .
The Rise and Fall of the Confederate Government ( 1881 ) is a book written by Jefferson Davis , who served as President of the Confederate States of America during the American Civil War .
Charlie and the Great Glass Elevator is a children 's book by British author Roald Dahl .
The Outermost House is a book by naturalist writer Henry Beston .
There 's a Boy in the Girls ' Bathroom is a juvenile fiction book from the author Louis Sachar .
Alphabet of Dreams ( 2006 ) is a novel by an American novelist Susan Fletcher .
Yellow Eyes is a novel in John Ringo 's Legacy of the Aldenata series , co - authored with Tom Kratman .
Seventeenth Summer is a novel written by Maureen Daly and published in 1942 .
Swallows and Amazons is the first book in the Swallows and Amazons series by English author Arthur Ransome ; it was first published in 1930 , with the action taking place in the summer of 1929 in the Lake District .
The Canon 's Yeoman 's Tale is one of The Canterbury Tales by Geoffrey Chaucer .
A Child 's Garden of Verses is a collection of poetry for children by the Scottish author Robert Louis Stevenson .
`` The Cop and the Anthem '' is a December 1904 short story by the United States author O. Henry .
Far from Medina ( French : Loin de Médine ) is a 1991 novel by the Algerian writer Assia Djebar .
Beef , No Chicken is a two - act play by Caribbean playwright Derek Walcott , written in 1981 .
The Ice People is a 1998 science fiction novel by Maggie Gee , set in a future world dominated by a new ice age .
The Southern Harmony , and Musical Companion is a shape note hymn and tune book compiled by William Walker , first published in 1835 .
Paul et Virginie ( or Paul and Virginia ) is a novel by Jacques - Henri Bernardin de Saint - Pierre , first published in 1788 .
Pertemuan Jodoh ( ( pərtəˈmuan dʒɔˈdɔh ) ; English : A Meeting of Soulmates ) is an Indonesian novel by Abdul Muis originally published in 1932 .
The Ballad of Abu Ghraib is a nonfiction book by American writer Philip Gourevitch .
Superfudge is a children 's novel by Judy Blume , published in 1980 .
God of Carnage ( originally in French Le Dieu du carnage ) is a play by Yasmina Reza .
Princess of the Midnight Ball is a 2009 young adult fantasy novel written by Jessica Day George .
Remarks on Colour ( German : Bemerkungen über die Farben ) was one of Ludwig Wittgenstein last works written during a visit to Vienna in 1950 while dying of cancer .
What 's Done in the Dark is a play written and directed by American playwright Tyler Perry .
The Diamond Brothers is a series of humorous children 's detective books by Anthony Horowitz , the first of which was published in 1986 .
The Sky Lords ( 1988 ) is a science fiction novel by Australian author , John Brosnan .
Moment in Peking is a novel originally written in English by Chinese author Lin Yutang .
The New Woman ( Polish : Emancypantki ) is the third of four major novels by the Polish writer Bolesław Prus .
The Nano Flower is a novel by Peter F. Hamilton , published on 10 March 1995 .
Too Many Magicians is a novel by Randall Garrett , an American science fiction author .
The Godfather Returns is a novel written by author Mark Winegardner , published in 2004 .
`` Worms of the Earth '' is a short story by American fantasy fiction writer Robert E. Howard .
The Marxists is a 1962 book about Marxism by sociologist C. Wright Mills .
From Potter 's Field is a crime fiction novel by Patricia Cornwell .
What Color is Your Parachute ? by Richard Nelson Bolles is a book for job - seekers that has been in print since 1970 and has been revised every year since 1975 , sometimes substantially .
Mad White Giant : a journey to the heart of the Amazon jungle is a 1985 semi - autobiographical adventure novel by British explorer and author Benedict Allen .
`` A Hunger Artist '' ( `` Ein Hungerkünstler '' ) is a short story by Franz Kafka first published in Die neue Rundschau in 1922 .
Damia 's Children is a 1993 science fiction novel by Anne McCaffrey , forming part of the Talent series .
The first story is `` The Parrot Who Met Papa '' by Ray Bradbury .
Rabindra Chitravali is a four - volume set of books by art historian R. Siva Kumar that contains paintings of Rabindranth Tagore .
The Lydian Chromatic Concept of Tonal Organization is a 1953 jazz music theory book written by George Russell .
Of Whom the World was Not Worthy is an English - language novel written by award - winning American author and psychologist Marie Chapian .
The Puppet Masters is a 1951 science fiction novel by Robert A. Heinlein in which American secret agents battle parasitic invaders from outer space .
The Taqwacores is the debut novel by Michael Muhammad Knight , depicting a fictitious Islamic punk rock scene .
`` Once a Week Wo n't Kill You '' is a short story by American author J. D. Salinger .
Cola Cola jazz is a novel by Togolese author Kangni Alem .
Fearless , A Novel of Sarah Bowman is a 1998 novel of historical fiction by Lucia St. Clair Robson .
The Saxon Stories ( also known as `` Saxon Tales''/``Saxon Chronicles '' in the USA and `` The Warrior Chronicles '' and since the BBC TV adaptation as `` The Last Kingdom Series '' in the UK ) is a continuing historical novel series written by Bernard Cornwell about 9th and 10th century Britain .
Extra Credit is a 2009 children 's novel written by Andrew Clements .
Casualties of Peace , published in 1966 , is Irish writer Edna O'Brien 's fifth novel .
The Rain Goddess is a novel by Peter Stiff ( ISBN 978 - 1919854069 ) , set in the war - torn area of Southern Rhodesia 's ( now Zimbabwe ) north - east border .
The Parasites is a novel by Daphne du Maurier , first published in 1949 .
The Strange Death of Tory England is a book of political commentary by the journalist Geoffrey Wheatcroft , published in 2005 .
The Space Merchants is a science fiction novel , written by Frederik Pohl and Cyril M. Kornbluth in 1952 .
A Card from Morocco is a novel written by author and actor Robert Shaw .
Hitler 's War is a biographical book by David Irving .
The Golden Volcano ( French : Le Volcan d'or ) is a novel by Jules Verne , published posthumously and edited by his son Michel Verne .
El derecho de matar ( `` The Right To Kill '' ) is an Argentine novel by Raúl Barón Biza .
NOS4A2 ( pronounced Nosferatu ) is the third novel by American author Joe Hill .
Barlowe 's Guide to Extraterrestrials is a 1979 science fiction book by artist Wayne Barlowe , with Ian Summers and Beth Meacham ( who provided the text ) .
The Hot Kid is a novel written by popular , contemporary crime - fiction author Elmore Leonard .
The Birth of Biopolitics is a part of a lecture series by French philosopher Michel Foucault at the Collège de France between 1978 and 1979 and published posthumously based on audio recordings .
Mémoires de deux jeunes mariées ( Letters of Two Brides ) is an epistolary novel by the French writer Honoré de Balzac .
Chuang Tse and the First Emperor is a novel by Italian writer Anna Russo .
Have You Been to the Beach Lately ? is a young adult book of poetry by Ralph Fletcher with photographs by Andrea Sperling .
The Tommyknockers is a 1987 science fiction novel by Stephen King .
The Last Space Viking is a science fiction novel written by John F. Carr and Mike Robertson , a sequel to H. Beam Piper 's Space Viking , and is set in Piper 's Terro - Human future history .
My Son the Fanatic is a short story written by Hanif Kureishi first published in The New Yorker in 1994 .
On Narcissism ( German : Zur Einführung des Narzißmus ) is a 1914 essay by Sigmund Freud , widely considered an introduction to Freud 's theories of narcissism .
Hippias Minor ( Greek : Ἱππίας ἐλάττων ) , or On Lying , is thought to be one of Plato 's early works .
The Blind Man of Seville is a 2003 crime novel and thriller by British writer Robert Wilson .
While I 'm Dead Feed the Dog is a comedic novel written by Ric Browde , published by Harper Collins in 2000 .
The Filocolo ( orig . Il Filocolo ) is a novel written by Giovanni Boccaccio between 1335 - 36 .
`` The Inverted Forest '' is a novella by J. D. Salinger , first published in Cosmopolitan magazine in December 1947 , and republished in Cosmopolitan 's `` Diamond Jubilee '' issue in March 1961 .
Državna Tajna ( English : State Secret ) is a book by Semir Halilović , son of Bosnian general Sefer Halilović , published in 2005 .
If Women Counted ( 1988 ) by Marilyn Waring , former New Zealand Member of Parliament , is an influential book in academic feminism , political economy and feminist economics .
Giacomo Joyce is a posthumously - published work by Irish writer James Joyce .
The Four Reigns ( Thai สี่แผ่นดิน , Si Phaen Din ) , a novel by Kukrit Pramoj , shows how individuals in Thai society adjust to change in the face of historic events .
Floating Dragon is the seventh novel by author Peter Straub , originally published by Underwood - Miller in November 1982 and G.P. Putnam 's Sons in February 1983 .
You Must Be Kidding is a crime thriller novel of 1979 by English author James Hadley Chase .
Geography Club is a 2003 young adult novel by American author Brent Hartinger .
Amadis of Greece ( Amadís de Grecia ) is a tale of knight - errantry written by Feliciano de Silva , a `` sequel - specialist '' who continued the adventures of Amadis de Gaula in this ninth installment .
A Shropshire Lad is a collection of sixty - three poems by the English poet Alfred Edward Housman ( 26 March 1859 -- 30 April 1936 ) .
The Cat Who Came to Breakfast ( 1994 ) is the sixteenth mystery novel by Lilian Jackson Braun , one of the Cat Who series .
Jungle Lovers ( 1971 ) is the fifth novel by American author Paul Theroux and set in post - colonial Malawi .
La Presqu’île ( translated as The Peninsula , 1970 ) is the title of a collection of three short pieces by French writer Julien Gracq that takes its name from its second work , a novella , which is preceded by La Route and followed by Le Roi Cophetua .
La fièvre is the title of a set of short stories written in French by French Nobel laureate J. M. G. Le Clézio and translated into English by Daphne Woodward as Fever and published by Atheneum .
The team first appears in Relative Heroes # 1 ( March 2000 ) , by Devin K. Grayson and Yvel Guichet .
My Year is a book by Roald Dahl and was published in 1993 .
The Three Evangelists ( Debout les Morts ) is a 1995 novel by French author Fred Vargas , translated into English in 2006 .
The Red Necklace is a young adult historical novel by Sally Gardner , published by Orion in 2007 .
The Viscount of Adrilankha is a fantasy novel published in three volumes and written by Steven Brust .
Search for a Method or The Problem of Method ( French : Questions de méthode ) is a 1957 essay by Jean - Paul Sartre in which he attempts to reconcile Marxism with existentialism .
The Eagle Has Landed is a book by British writer Jack Higgins , set during World War II and first published in 1975 .
Jack Cross was a comic book series written by Warren Ellis and drawn by Gary Erskine .
Dream Stuff is a collection of short stories by the Australian writer David Malouf , published in 2000 .
Modern Dance for Beginners is a play for two people written by British playwright Sarah Phelps .
The Last Patriot is a thriller written by American novelist Brad Thor .
Dacica ( or De bello dacico ) is a Latin work by Roman Emperor Trajan , written in the spirit of Julius Caesar 's commentaries like De Bello Gallico , and describing Trajan 's campaigns in Dacia .
Apartment 255 is a 2001 Ned Kelly Award winning novel by the Australian author Bunty Avieson .
Behind the Evidence is a science fiction novel by authors Amelia Reynolds Long and William L. Crawford writing under the pseudonym Peter Reynolds .
`` The Piece of String '' ( French : La Ficelle ) is an 1883 short story by Guy de Maupassant .
The Supernatural Enhancements is a 2014 horror / mystery novel and the English language literary debut of Spanish cartoonist and author Edgar Cantero .
The Boy in the Bush is a novel by D. H. Lawrence set in Western Australia , first published in 1924 .
The King of Torts ( 2003 ) is a legal / suspense novel written by American author John Grisham .
Mr Ponsonby is the fourth novel from noted New Zealand author Ian Middleton , and is described as `` his eulogy to a gentrifying Ponsonby '' .
Crucial Instances is Edith Wharton 's classic 1901 short story collection .
Sidereus Nuncius ( usually Sidereal Messenger , also Starry Messenger or Sidereal Message ) is a short astronomical treatise ( or pamphlet ) published in New Latin by Galileo Galilei on March 13th , 1610 .
The Sheltering Sky is a 1949 novel of post - colonial alienation and existential despair by American writer and composer Paul Bowles .
Dark Congress is an original novel based on the American television series Buffy the Vampire Slayer , and is written by Christopher Golden .
Jerusalem the Golden is a novel by Margaret Drabble published in 1967 , and is a winner of the James Tait Black Memorial Prize in 1967 .
The Power of Shazam ! is a 1994 hardcover graphic novel , written and painted by Jerry Ordway for DC Comics .
When Patty Went to College is Jean Webster 's first novel , published in 1903 .
The Pushcart War is a popular children 's novel by the American writer Jean Merrill , illustrated by Ronni Solbert and published by Harper & Row in 1964 .
Cutter and Bone is a 1976 thriller novel by Newton Thornburg about a Vietnam veteran , Alex Cutter , who tries to convince his friend , Richard Bone , that Bone witnessed a murder .
The Marzipan Pig ( 1986 , ISBN 0 - 374 - 34859 - 6 ) is a children 's book by Russell Hoban .
Miniatures Handbook was authored by Jonathan Tweet , Mike Donais , Skaff Elias , and Rob Heinsoo , and published by Wizards of the Coast in October 2003 .
Versuch die Metamorphose der Pflanzen zu erklären , known in English as Metamorphosis of Plants , was published by German poet and philosopher Johann Wolfgang von Goethe in 1790 .
Family Devotions is a 1981 play by American playwright David Henry Hwang .
The Red Horse ( Italian : Il cavallo rosso , 1983 ) is an epic novel written by Eugenio Corti that follows an industrial family , the Rivas , in Nomana starting from the end of May 1940 through World War II and the new democratic Italy .
The Magic School Bus In the Time of the Dinosaurs is the sixth book in Joanna Cole and Bruce Degan 's The Magic School Bus series .
The Enemy in the Blanket ( 1958 ) is the second novel in Anthony Burgess 's Malayan Trilogy The Long Day Wanes .
The Comentarios Reales de los Incas is a book written by Inca Garcilaso de la Vega , the first published mestizo writer of colonial Andean South America .
The Continent of Circe ( 1965 ) is a book of essays written by Indian author Nirad C. Chaudhuri that was winner of the Duff Cooper Prize for 1966 .
The Subterraneans is a 1958 novella by Beat Generation author Jack Kerouac .
Wartime Lies is a semi - autobiographical novel by Louis Begley first published in 1991 .
The Last American Vampire is an action horror novel by Seth Grahame - Smith and a sequel to Abraham Lincoln , Vampire Hunter , released on January 13 , 2015 , through New York -- based publishing company Grand Central Publishing .
Invaders from the Infinite is a science fiction novel by author John W. Campbell , Jr ..
`` Tradition and the Individual Talent '' ( 1919 ) is an essay written by poet and literary critic T. S. Eliot .
My Ishmael is a 1997 novel by Daniel Quinn : a followup to Ishmael .

In eminenti apostolatus specula was a papal bull issued by Pope Clement XII on 28 April 1738 , banning Catholics from becoming Freemasons .
How German Is It ( Wie Deutsch ist es ) is a novel by Walter Abish , published in 1980 .
The Mangan Inheritance , published in 1979 , is a novel by Northern Irish - Canadian writer Brian Moore .
The Athenian Murders is an historical mystery novel written by Spanish author José Carlos Somoza .
What Maisie Knew is a novel by Henry James , first published as a serial in the Chap - Book and ( revised and abridged ) in the New Review in 1897 and then as a book later that year .
Middlemarch , A Study of Provincial Life is a novel by English author George Eliot , first published in eight instalments ( volumes ) during 1871 - -2 .
The Castaways of the Flag ( French : Seconde patrie , lit . Second Fatherland , 1900 ) is an adventure novel written by Jules Verne .
Charlie Chan Carries On ( 1930 ) is the fifth novel in the Charlie Chan series by Earl Derr Biggers .
Of Walking In Ice is the diary of German film director Werner Herzog published in 1978 .
The Life and Loves of a She - Devil is a 1983 novel by British feminist author Fay Weldon about a highly unattractive woman who goes to great lengths to take revenge on her husband and his attractive lover .
Offending the Audience is a play by Austrian writer Peter Handke .
William 's Doll is a 1972 children 's picture book by Charlotte Zolotow about a boy who wants a doll even though dolls typically are considered a toy only for girls .
Brideshead Revisited , The Sacred & Profane Memories of Captain Charles Ryder is a novel by English writer Evelyn Waugh , first published in 1945 .
Philosophical Explanations is a 1981 metaphysical , epistemological , and ethical treatise by Robert Nozick .
The American Prisoner is a British novel written by Eden Phillpotts and published in 1904 and adapted into a film by the same name in 1929 .
The Roads to Freedom ( French : Les chemins de la liberté ) is a series of novels by Jean - Paul Sartre .
Scotland 's Story is book by Henrietta Elizabeth Marshall first published in 1906 in the United Kingdom and in 1910 in the United States .
Once Were Warriors is New Zealand author Alan Duff 's bestselling first novel , published in 1990 .
`` A Legend of Old Egypt '' ( Polish : `` Z legend dawnego Egiptu '' ) is a short story by Bolesław Prus , originally published January 1 , 1888 , in New Year 's supplements to the Warsaw Kurier Codzienny ( Daily Courier ) and Tygodnik Ilustrowany ( Illustrated Weekly ) .
The Adventures of Jodelle ( original title Les Aventures de Jodelle ) is a 1966 French erotic comic drawn by Guy Peellaert and scripted by Pierre Bartier .
`` The Mirrors of Tuzun Thune '' is one of the original short stories about Kull of Atlantis , written by American author Robert E. Howard and first published in Weird Tales magazine c. 1929 .
Hamlet 's Father is a 2008 novella by Orson Scott Card , which retells the story of Shakespeare 's Hamlet in modernist prose , and which makes several changes to the characters ' motivations and backstory .
In Praise of the Stepmother is an erotic novel by Peruvian writer Mario Vargas Llosa , winner of the Nobel Prize in Literature in 2010 .
The Polysyllabic Spree is a 2004 collection of Nick Hornby 's `` Stuff I 've Been Reading '' columns in The Believer .
Lovecraft 's Book is a historical novel by author Richard A. Lupoff .
Die Hochzeit ( The Wedding , WWV 31 ) is an unfinished opera by Richard Wagner which predates his completed works in the genre .
Bill Bergson ( original Swedish name : Kalle Blomkvist ) is a fictional boy detective created by Swedish writer Astrid Lindgren .
Executive Orders is a political and military thriller novel by Tom Clancy .
The Russian Debutante 's Handbook was the debut novel by author Gary Shteyngart , published in 2002 .
Principles of Mathematical Logic is the 1950 American translation of the 1938 second edition of David Hilbert 's and Wilhelm Ackermann 's classic text Grundzüge der theoretischen Logik , on elementary mathematical logic .
My Father 's Wives is a novel by the Angolan author José Eduardo Agualusa published in 2008 by Arcadia Books ( London , England ) .
The Tales of Ensign Stål ( Swedish original title : Fänrik Ståls sägner , Finnish : Vänrikki Stoolin tarinat , or year 2007 translation Vänrikki Stålin tarinat ) is an epic poem written in Swedish by the Finland - Swedish author Johan Ludvig Runeberg , the national poet of Finland .
The Ultimate Revelations is an Islamic science fiction novel by Jamshed Akhtar .
Topless in Philadelphia is a one man comedy stage play by Miles Tredinnick .
Missing Kissinger is a second book by Etgar Keret .
The Hessian is a 1972 novel by Howard Fast set in the time of the American Revolution .
King Leopold 's Soliloquy is a 1905 pamphlet by Mark Twain .
A Christian Turn'd Turk ( 1612 ) is a play by the English dramatist Robert Daborne .
Six Thinking Hats is a system designed by Edward de Bono which describes a tool for group discussion and individual thinking involving six colored hats .
Freaky Friday is a classic comedic children 's novel written by Mary Rodgers , first published in the United States in 1972 , and adapted for film several times .
The Pirates ! in an Adventure with the Romantics is the fifth novel in Gideon Defoe 's The Pirates ! series .
Listening for Lions is a children 's novel by Gloria Whelan , first published in 2005 .

Before I Go to Sleep is the first novel by S. J. Watson published in Spring 2011 .

The Asylum Seeker ( Dutch : De asielzoeker ) is a novel by Dutch author Arnon Grunberg .
Angel and the Ape was a humor comic book created by E. Nelson Bridwell published by DC Comics .
The Oeconomicus ( Greek : Οἰκονομικός ) by Xenophon is a Socratic dialogue principally about household management and agriculture .
All the World 's Mornings ( French : Tous les matins du monde ) is a 1991 novel by Pascal Quignard .
Del - Del is a psychological young adult novel written by Australian author Victor Kelleher and published in 1992 .
When Things of the Spirit Come First is Simone de Beauvoir 's ' first ' work of fiction .
Children of the River is a young adult novel by Linda Crew published in 1989 .
Going Down Fast ( ISBN 0 - 449 - 24480 - 6 ) is a 1969 novel by Marge Piercy .
Phædo or Phaedo ( /ˈfiːdoʊ/ ; Greek : Φαίδων , Phaidōn , Greek pronunciation : ( pʰaídɔːn ) ) , also known to ancient readers as On The Soul , is one of the best - known dialogues of Plato 's middle period , along with the Republic and the Symposium .
Morning in the Burned House is a book of poetry by Canadian author Margaret Atwood , published by McClelland and Stewart in 1995 .
The Mighty Swordsmen is a 1970 anthology of fantasy short stories in the sword and sorcery subgenre , edited by Hans Stefan Santesson .
The Strode Venturer is a thriller by Hammond Innes published in 1965 .
In the Teeth of the Evidence is a collection of short stories by Dorothy L. Sayers first published by Victor Gollancz in 1939 .
Strangers in Paradise is a long - running , mostly self - published black - and - white comic book , written and drawn by Terry Moore .
The Threateners is the title of a spy novel by Donald Hamilton first published in 1992 .
The Grammar of Science is a book by Karl Pearson first published in hardback in 1892 .
The Pacific Between is a romantic coming of age novel by Raymond K. Wong .
On the Crown ( Ancient Greek : Ὑπὲρ Κτησιφῶντος περὶ τοῦ Στεφάνου ) is the most famous judicial oration of the prominent Athenian statesman and orator Demosthenes , delivered in 330 BC .
Mr Olim is a novel by Ernest Raymond , published to critical acclaim by Cassell in 1961 .
The Porcelain Fat Lady ( Spanish : La gorda de porcelana ) is a children 's story by the Chilean writer Isabel Allende .
Demons of the Deep is a single - player roleplaying gamebook written by Steve Jackson ( the American game designer , rather than the series co - creator ) , illustrated by Duncan Smith and originally published in 1984 by Puffin Books .
The Road of Bones is a 2006 young adult novel written by Anne Fine .
The Lives of Animals ( 1999 ) is a metafictional novella about animal rights by the South African novelist J. M. Coetzee , recipient of the 2003 Nobel Prize in Literature .
The Perilous Gard is an American young adult novel by Elizabeth Marie Pope , published in 1974 .
Night of Error is a First - person narrative novel written by English author Desmond Bagley , and was first published in 1984 .
Lost Laysen is a novella written by Margaret Mitchell in 1916 , although it was not published until 1996 .
Mr. Blettsworthy on Rampole Island is a 1928 novel by H. G. Wells .
Figure Away , first published in 1937 , is a detective story by Phoebe Atwood Taylor which features her series detective Asey Mayo , the `` Codfish Sherlock '' .
Gods and Pawns ( ISBN 0 - 765 - 31552 - 1 ) is a collection of stories written by Kage Baker and published by Tor Books .
A Further Range is a collection of poems by Robert Frost published in 1937 .
Dreamtigers , first published in 1960 as El Hacedor ( `` The Maker '' ) , is a collection of poems , short essays , and literary sketches by the Argentine author Jorge Luis Borges .
Tales from the Heart is the title of a series of comic books , written by Cindy Goff and Rafael Nieves and illustrated by Seitu Hayden .
The Wreck of the Zephyr is a children 's book written and illustrated by the American author Chris Van Allsburg , first published by Houghton Mifflin in March 1983 .

Borkmann 's Point ( Swedish : Borkmanns punkt ) is a prize - winning crime novel by Swedish writer Håkan Nesser , first published in Sweden in 1994 and translated into English by Laurie Thompson in 2006 .
The Ambassador 's Mission is a fantasy novel that was released on May 6 , 2010 in hardback by author Trudi Canavan .

Green Rider ( titled The Green Rider in some later printings ) is the first novel written by Kristen Britain and is the first book in its series .

The Voodoo Macbeth is a common nickname for the Federal Theatre Project 's 1936 New York production of William Shakespeare 's Macbeth .
Biographia Literaria , or in full Biographia Literaria ; or Biographical Sketches of MY LITERARY LIFE and OPINIONS , is an autobiography in discourse by Samuel Taylor Coleridge , which he published in 1817 , in two volumes .
The Tale of One Bad Rat is a 4-issue comic book limited series by Bryan Talbot .
The Last of Chéri ( French : La Fin de Chéri ) is a novel written by Colette .

The Lotus and the Storm is a novel about war and its casualties by Lan Cao .

Ashling is the third book in the Obernewtyn series by Isobelle Carmody .
Probability Sun is a 2001 science fiction novel by Nancy Kress , a sequel to her 2000 publication Probability Moon .
The Mentality of Apes by Wolfgang Köhler is a landmark work in ethology , cognitive psychology and the study of the anthropoid apes .
Coming into the Country is a 1976 book by John McPhee about Alaska and McPhee 's travels through much of the state with bush pilots , prospectors , and settlers , as well as politicians and businesspeople who each interpret the state in different ways .
Iron Empires is a science fiction comic series written and painted by the American artist Christopher Moeller .
`` Barn Burning '' is a short story by the American author William Faulkner which first appeared in Harper 's in 1939 and has since been widely anthologized .
Melting Stones , a fantasy novel by young adult author Tamora Pierce , was released by Full Cast Audio as an audiobook original in October 2007 , and was released in print form by Scholastic in the summer of 2008 .
The Colour of a Dog Running Away is a novel by the Welsh novelist Richard Gwyn published in 2005 .
When Gravity Fails is a cyberpunk science fiction novel by George Alec Effinger published in 1986 .
The Empty City is a 2012 children 's fantasy novel written under the pseudonym Erin Hunter .
Calico Joe is John Grisham 's first baseball novel .
Philosophy of Arithmetic ( PA ; German : Philosophie der Arithmetik . Psychologische und logische untersuchungen ) is Edmund Husserl 's first published book .
The Moral Obligation to Be Intelligent is an influential essay , part of the essay collection The Moral Obligation to Be Intelligent , and Other Essays published in 1915 by John Erskine , English professor at Columbia University .
Place Called Estherville is a novel written by Erskine Caldwell , most famous for his novels Tobacco Road and God 's Little Acre .
Three Tales of Horror is an illustrated collection of stories by American author H. P. Lovecraft .
Mariana Pineda is a play by the Spanish playwright and poet Federico García Lorca .
The novel The Story of the Last Thought ( in German Das Märchen vom letzten Gedanken ) of the German - Jewish writer Edgar Hilsenrath is about the Armenian Genocide in 1915 .
`` Blue Tigers '' ( Spanish : Tigres azules ) is a short story by Argentine writer and poet Jorge Luis Borges .
Blood Red , Snow White is a historical novel by Marcus Sedgwick published in 2007 .
Just Tricking ! is the first volume in the Just ! series written by Andy Griffiths .
Gil Jourdan is a Belgian detective comic strip created by Maurice Tillieux .
Ídolos rotos ( Broken Idols ) is a novel by the Venezuelan writer Manuel Díaz Rodríguez that was published in 1901 .
Inner Experience ( French : L'expérience intérieure ) is a 1943 book by Georges Bataille , his first lengthy philosophical treatise .
Further Adventures of Lad , also known as Dog Stories Every Child Should Know , is a 1922 American novel written by Albert Payson Terhune and published by George H. Doran .
Silent Interviews is a 1995 collection of written interviews with author , professor , and critic Samuel R. Delany .
The Fourth Realm Trilogy refers to the trilogy of books written by pseudonymous author John Twelve Hawks and published between 2004 ( in the UK , 2005 in the US ) and 2009 .
Animal Ark is a children 's book series written by a collection of authors under the direction of Ben M. Baglio using the pseudonym Lucy Daniels starting in 1994 .
Studies in the Philosophy of Marxism ( Russian : Очерки по философии Марксизма ) was an account of a seminar held by Vladimir Bazarov , Alexander Bogdanov , Anatoly Lunacharsky , Jakov Berman , Osip Gelfond , Pavlov Yushkevich and Sergey Suvorov ( 1869 - 1918 ) published in St Petersburg in 1908 .
The Fight for Manod ( ISBN 0701208090 ) is a 1979 novel by Raymond Williams .
The Valorous Years is a serial novella by A. J. Cronin , initially published in 1940 in Good Housekeeping magazine .
An Evening of Long Goodbyes is a 2003 comic novel by Irish author Paul Murray .
It Happened in Boston ? ( 1968 ) is a novel by Russell H. Greenan .
Jhegaala is the eleventh book in Steven Brust′s Vlad Taltos series , set in the fantasy world of Dragaera .
El Jetón is the final novel published by Salvadoran writer Arturo Ambrogi shortly before his death in 1936 .
Agnes of God is a play by John Pielmeier which tells the story of a novice nun who gives birth and insists that the child was the result of a virgin conception .
Tribal Scars is a collection of short stories by Senegalese author Ousmane Sembène .
Three Lives ( 1909 ) was American writer Gertrude Stein 's first published book .
The Last Canadian is a 1974 science fiction novel by William C. Heine about the adventures of Eugene Arnprior after North America is devastated by a plague .
`` Annabel Lee '' is the last complete poem composed by American author Edgar Allan Poe .
The Wanderground is a speculative fiction novel by Sally Miller Gearhart , published in 1979 by Persephone Books .
London Under is a 2012 book by British biographer , novelist , and critic Peter Ackroyd about the history of underground London .
Haroun and the Sea of Stories is a 1990 children 's book by Salman Rushdie .
Koštana ( Serbian : Коштана ) is a popular play , written by Borisav Stanković .
Les Mauvais Rêves ( English : Bad Dreams ) is the first album in the French comic book ( or bande dessinée ) science fiction series Valérian and Laureline created by writer Pierre Christin and artist Jean - Claude Mézières .
The Dream of the Mad Monkey ( Le rêve du singe fou ) is a novel by Christopher Frank , published in 1976 .
Night of the Grizzlies ( 1969 ) is a book by Jack Olsen which details events surrounding the night of August 13 , 1967 , when two young women were separately attacked in Glacier National Park , Montana , by grizzly bears .
Asinaria , which has been translated as The One with the Asses , is a comic play written in Latin by the Roman playwright Titus Maccius Plautus and is known as one of the great works of ancient Roman comedy .
Meteor ! is a 1987 children 's picture book by author Patricia Polacco .
The Story of a Soul ( l'Histoire d'une Âme ) is the autobiography of Thérèse of Lisieux , a French Discalced Carmelite nun , later recognized as a saint .
The Complete Peanuts is a series of books containing the entire run of Charles M. Schulz 's long - running newspaper comic strip Peanuts .
Woodsong is a book of memoirs by Gary Paulsen .
Honus & Me is a children 's novel by Dan Gutman , published in 1997 , and the first in the Baseball Card Adventures series .
Dragonsdale is a fantasy novel written by The Two Steves ( Steve Barlow and Steve Skidmore ) under the pen name `` Salamanda Drake '' and published by Scholastic in 2007 .
Those Barren Leaves is a satirical novel by Aldous Huxley , published in 1925 .
The Illustrated Bible Dictionary , better known as Easton 's Bible Dictionary , is a reference work on topics related to the Christian Bible compiled by Matthew George Easton .
Invasion of the Sea ( French : L'Invasion de la mer ) is an adventure novel written by Jules Verne .
Balder Dead is a narrative poem with powerful tragic themes , first published in 1855 by Matthew Arnold .
Mrs. Eckdorf in O'Neill 's Hotel is a novel written by William Trevor , first published by The Bodley Head in 1969 .
The Meditations of the Emperor Marcus Aurelius Antoninus .
Skallagrigg is a 1987 novel written by William Horwood and influenced by Horwood 's relationship with his own daughter Rachel , who has cerebral palsy .
The English Spy is the fifteenth in Daniel Silva 's Gabriel Allon series .
My Name Is Anne , She Said , Anne Frank is a 2003 memoir - book written by Jacqueline van Maarsen .
Madame Two Swords is a fantasy novelette by Tanith Lee .
The Beast House is a 1986 horror novel by American author Richard Laymon .
`` Waterspider '' is a science fiction short story by Philip K. Dick , first published in 1964 in If magazine .
The Salt Eaters is a 1980 novel , the first such work by Toni Cade Bambara .
Safari Adventure is a 1966 children 's book by the Canadian - born American author Willard Price featuring his `` Adventure '' series characters , Hal and Roger Hunt .
The Ship Who Sang ( 1969 ) is a science fiction novel by Anne McCaffrey , a fix - up of five stories published 1961 to 1969 .
The Monsters of Morley Manor ( sometimes subtitled A Madcap Adventure ) is a children 's fantasy / sci - fi / horror novel written by Bruce Coville , published in 2001 .
The Trail of Blood ( 1931 ) is a booklet by the Baptist minister , James Milton Carroll .
Black Boy ( 1946 ) is a memoir by Richard Wright , detailing his youth and his eventual move to Chicago , where he establishes his writing career and becomes involved with the Communist Party .
The Owl Service is a low fantasy novel for young adults by Alan Garner , published by Collins in 1967 .
Zündels Abgang ( Zündel 's Departure ) is the first novel of Swiss writer Markus Werner ( 1944 in Eschlikon ) , that was published in 1984 and became a bestseller and enjoys the status of cult novel for a lot of readers .
In the Mouth of the Whale is a 2012 science fiction novel by Paul J. McAuley , the third in his Quiet War sequence .
The Blue Man is a mystery , science fiction novel written by American author Kin Platt .
One Amazing Thing is a 2010 novel by award - winning novelist and poet Chitra Banerjee Divakaruni .
`` Critical Factor '' is a science fiction short story written by Hal Clement , and published in 1953 .
The House of Lost Identity is a collection of short stories by Donald Corley , illustrated by the author .
Pegasus in Space ( 2000 ) is a science fiction novel by Anne McCaffrey , set in her `` Talents Universe '' .
Territorial Rights is a novel by Scottish author Muriel Spark published in 1979 .
A Lady of Quality is a novel published in 1896 by Frances Hodgson Burnett that was the second highest best - selling book in the United States in 1896 .
Holiday at the Dew Drop Inn is the third and final book in the series by Eve Garnett which began with the award - winning The Family from One End Street in 1937 , and continued with the long - delayed Further Adventures of the Family from One End Street ( published in 1956 ) .
The Wives of Israel will be the fourth novel in the Women of Genesis series by Orson Scott Card .
Delusion and Dream in Jensen 's Gradiva ( German : Der Wahn und die Träume in W. Jensens `` Gradiva '' ) is an essay written in 1907 by Sigmund Freud that subjects the novel Gradiva by Wilhelm Jensen , and especially its protagonist , to psychoanalysis .
The Clean House is a play by Sarah Ruhl , which premiered in 2004 at Yale Repertory Theatre , was produced Off - Broadway in 2006 , and has since been produced in many theaters .
Memoirs of Modern Philosophers is a novel by British author Elizabeth Hamilton published in 1800 .
Antic Hay is a comic novel by Aldous Huxley , published in 1923 .
Against Leptines was a speech give by Demosthenes in which he called for the repeal of a law sponsored by Leptines which denied anyone a special exemption from paying public charges ( leitourgiai ) .
A Decayed Family ( Захуда′лый род , Zakhudaly rod ) is an unfinished novel by Nikolai Leskov , subtitled `` The Family Chronicles of Princes Protazanov '' .
The Search for the Red Dragon , by James A. Owen , is a fantasy novel released on January 1 , 2008 .
Harlot 's Ghost ( 1991 ) is a fictional chronicle of the Central Intelligence Agency by Norman Mailer .
Siebenkäs is a German Romantic novel by Jean Paul , published in Berlin in three volumes between 1796 and 1797 .
Love Creeps ( 2005 ) is the third novel by American writer Amanda Filipacchi .
Barbapapa is both the title character , and name of the `` species '' of said character , of a series of children 's books written in the 1970s by Annette Tison and Talus Taylor , who resided in Paris , France .
Garden of the Purple Dragon is a children 's fantasy novel by Carole Wilkinson , published in September 2005 by Macmillan Publishers .
Strange Brother is a gay novel written by Blair Niles published in 1931 .
The Last Dodo is a BBC Books original novel written by Jacqueline Rayner and based on the long running science fiction television series Doctor Who .
The Fourth Bear is a mystery / fantasy novel by Jasper Fforde published in July 2006 .
The Time Machine Did It ( ISBN 0 - 9755799 - 0 - 8 ) is a comic novel by American author John Swartzwelder , known for his work on popular cartoon sitcom The Simpsons .
A Study in Scarlet is an 1887 detective novel by British author Arthur Conan Doyle .
The Kitchen God 's Wife is the second novel by Chinese - American author , Amy Tan .
Baby Is Three is a science fiction novella by Theodore Sturgeon , first published in the October 1952 issue of Galaxy magazine .
Shall We Tell the President ? is a 1977 novel by English author Jeffrey Archer .
A Rather English Marriage is a novel by Angela Lambert , first published in 1992 , and later adapted for television by Andrew Davies for the BBC .
Scenes of Clerical Life is the title under which George Eliot 's first published fictional work , a collection of three short stories , was released in book form ; it was the first of her works to be released under her famous pseudonym .
Motl , Peysi the Cantor 's Son subtitled The Writings of an Orphan Boy ( מאָטל פּייסי דעם חזנס ; כתבֿים פֿון אַ ייִנגל אַ יתום -- motl peysi dem khazns ; ksovim fun a yingl a yosem ) was the last novel by the Yiddish author Sholem Aleichem , and unfinished at the time of his death .
The Under Dog and Other Stories is a short story collection written by Agatha Christie and first published in the United Kingdom in 1929 by The Reader 's Library .
The Rider is a short Ruritanian romance by Edgar Rice Burroughs .
Little Wizard Stories of Oz is a set of six short stories written for young children by L. Frank Baum , the creator of the Oz books .
Seven Myths of the Spanish Conquest is a 2003 work by ethnohistorian Matthew Restall in which he posits that there are seven myths about the Spanish colonization of the Americas that have come to be widely believed to be true .
The Killing Star is a hard science fiction novel by Charles R. Pellegrino and George Zebrowski , published in April , 1995 .
Amnesiascope is a 1996 novel by Steve Erickson .
Flyte is a 2006 children 's novel by Angie Sage and the second book in the Septimus Heap series .
The Summer Son is a 2011 novel by Craig Lancaster , and the second novel by the author .
The Passionate Pilgrim ( 1599 ) is an anthology of 20 poems collected and published by William Jaggard that were attributed to `` W. Shakespeare '' on the title page , only five of which are considered authentically Shakespearean .
Sam Steele 's Adventures on Land and Sea is a juvenile adventure novel written by L. Frank Baum , famous as the creator of the Land of Oz . The book was Baum 's first effort at writing specifically for an audience of adolescent boys , a market he would pursue in the coming years of his career .
My Father 's Glory ( French : La Gloire de mon père ) is a 1957 autobiographical novel by Marcel Pagnol .
Becoming Madame Mao is a historical novel by Anchee Min detailing the life of Jiang Qing .
A Treatise on Money is a work on economics by English economist John Maynard Keynes .
Chicken with Plums ( Poulet aux prunes in the original French version ) is a graphic novel by Iranian author Marjane Satrapi .
The Robe is a 1942 historical novel about the Crucifixion of Jesus written by Lloyd C. Douglas .
`` The Three Clever Kings '' is a children 's fairytale from the anthology The Necklace of Princess Fiorimonde that was written by Mary De Morgan .
Midnight 's Choice is a fantasy novel for young adults , by Kate Thompson .
Max and the Cats is a 1981 novella by Brazilian writer and physician Moacyr Scliar .
The Octagonal Raven is a 2001 science fiction novel by L. E. Modesitt , Jr.
Mary 's Land , by Lucia St. Clair Robson , is a 1995 historical novel , set in the year 1638 .
I Love You , Beth Cooper is a comedy novel written by former The Simpsons writer Larry Doyle .
`` The Yazoo Queen '' ( 2003 ) is a fantasy short story by Orson Scott Card set in his The Tales of Alvin Maker series .
The New Annotated Sherlock Holmes is a series of three annotated books edited by Leslie S. Klinger , collecting all of Arthur Conan Doyle 's short stories and novels about Sherlock Holmes .
Funny Money is a farce written by Ray Cooney .
The Fear Index is a 2011 novel by British author Robert Harris .
Touch the Dark is the first book in The Cassandra Palmer series , written by best - selling author Karen Chance .
The Life Lottery , a futuristic eco - thriller , is the final book in Ian Irvine 's Human Rites Sequence , set after the events in Terminator Gene , it is also only published in Australia and currently out of print , but will be re - released as a revised edition in March 2010 .
The Fifth Head of Cerberus is the title of both a novella and a single - volume collection of three novellas , written by American science fiction and fantasy author Gene Wolfe , both published in 1972 .
A Sense of Where You Are , by John McPhee , profiles Bill Bradley during Bradley 's senior year at Princeton University .
Jewtopia is a comedic play by Bryan Fogel and Sam Wolfson .
Distrust That Particular Flavor is a collection of non - fiction writing by speculative fiction author William Gibson .
The Ancestor Cell is a novel by Peter Anghelides and Stephen Cole , based on the science fiction television series Doctor Who .
Golden Son is a 2015 science fiction novel by American author Pierce Brown , the second in his forthcoming Red Rising trilogy .
Murder in the Cassava Patch ( 1968 ) is a novella by Liberian Bai T. Moore .
Moon Tiger is a 1987 novel by Penelope Lively which spans the time before , during and after World War II . The novel won the 1987 Booker Prize .
Memories of a Catholic Girlhood is the autobiography of Mary McCarthy that was published in 1957 .
Nerilka 's Story is a science fiction novella by the American - Irish author Anne McCaffrey .
`` Planet of the Symbiotes '' is a five - issue comic book story - arc written by David Michelinie and published by Marvel Comics in 1995 .
Emus Ca n't Walk Backwards is the sequel to Robert Anwood 's 2006 book Bears Ca n't Run Downhill .
The People of the Abyss ( 1903 ) is a book by Jack London about life in the East End of London in 1902 .
Tonight , by Sea is a young adult novel written by Frances Temple , published in 1995 .
Space Viking is a science fiction novel written by H. Beam Piper and is set in his Terro - Human future history .
The Theosophical Glossary by Helena Blavatsky was first published in 1892 .
Waiting for Sunrise is a 2012 espionage novel by William Boyd .
The Blair Years is a book by Alastair Campbell , featuring extracts from his diaries detailing the period during which he worked for Tony Blair .
A Key to the Suite is a novel by American author John D. MacDonald first published in 1962 by Fawcett Publications .
The Indigo Spell is a fiction novel written by the American author Richelle Mead .
Deadman 's Road is a collection of one novel and four novellas by American writer Joe R. Lansdale .
Zuiweng Tingji ( simplified Chinese : 醉翁亭记 ; traditional Chinese : 醉翁亭記 ; pinyin : Zùiwēng Tíng Jì ; literally : `` An Account of the Old Toper 's Pavilion '' ) is a semi - autobiographical poem by Ouyang Xiu ( 1007 - -1072 CE ) .
My Lord John is an unfinished historical fiction novel by the British author Georgette Heyer , published posthumously in 1975 after her death the previous year .
Steps to an Ecology of Mind is a collection of Gregory Bateson 's short works over his long and varied career .
Means of Evil is a collection of short stories by British writer Ruth Rendell .
Straight White Male , a novel by California writer Gerald Haslam , won the Western States Arts Federation Book Award for Fiction and the Foreword Magazine Award in 2000 .
Anne of Geierstein , or The Maiden of the Mist ( 1829 ) is a novel by Sir Walter Scott .
Brown Girl Dreaming is a 2014 adolescent novel told in verse by author Jacqueline Woodson .
Quelques Portraits - Sonnets de Femmes is a poetry chapbook , by Natalie Clifford Barney , with watercolor illustrations by Alice Pike Barney .
DNA Repair and Mutagenesis is a college - level textbook about DNA repair and mutagenesis written by Errol Friedberg , Graham Walker , Wolfram Siede , Richard D. Wood , and Roger Schultz .
The Blue Air Compressor is a short story by Stephen King , first published in January 1971 in Onan Magazine ( University of Maine ) .
Magic Street ( 2005 ) is an urban fantasy novel by Orson Scott Card .
Seven Little Monsters is a children 's picture book by American author and illustrator Maurice Sendak .
Contre Sainte - Beuve is an unfinished book of essays written by Marcel Proust .
The Modern Corporation and Private Property is a book written by Adolf Berle and Gardiner Means published in 1932 regarding the foundations of United States corporate law .
Pirate Freedom ( 2007 ) is a fantasy novel by Gene Wolfe about a young man who is transported back in time and becomes a pirate .
`` The Thriving Cult of Greed and Power '' is an article , written in 1991 by U.S. investigative journalist Richard Behar , which is highly critical of Scientology .
Sentimental Education ( French : L'Éducation sentimentale , 1869 ) is a novel by Gustave Flaubert , that is considered one of the most influential novels of the 19th century , being praised by contemporaries George Sand , Émile Zola , but criticised by Henry James .
The Fourth Philippic is a speech attributed to the Athenian statesman and orator , Demosthenes and given in 341 BC . It constitutes the last of the four philippics .
Arc d'X ( 1993 ) , by Steve Erickson , is an Avantpop novel .
Inside Himalaya is a large coffee - table style book containing pictures taken by Basil Pao , who was the stills photographer on the team that made the Himalaya with Michael Palin TV program for the BBC .
North to the Orient is a 1935 book by the American writer Anne Morrow Lindbergh .
Alaler Gharer Dulal ( published in 1857 ) is a Bengali novel by Peary Chand Mitra ( 1814 - 1883 ) .
Good Morning , Holy Spirit is a best - selling book by Benny Hinn on the person of the Holy Spirit .
Nine Coaches Waiting is a then - contemporary suspense , Gothic Romance novel by Mary Stewart published originally in 1958 .
A Change of Skin is a love story written by Carlos Fuentes about a Mexican writer , and his American Jewish wife .
The Shadow of Saganami is a science fiction novel by American writer David Weber , published in 2004 .
Marino Faliero , Doge of Venice is a blank verse tragedy in five acts by Lord Byron , published and first performed in 1821 .
Anno Dracula is a 1992 novel by British writer Kim Newman , the first in the Anno Dracula series .
7×7 Tales of a Sevensleeper ( German : Siebenschläfergeschichten ) is a 1985 children 's book written by Hanna Johansen .
A Singular Life is a novel published in 1895 by Elizabeth Stuart Phelps Ward .
Continuidad de los parques , or Continuity of the parks , is a short story in Spanish by Argentine writer Julio Cortázar ( 1914 - -1984 ) .
Among the Brave is a 2004 book by Margaret Peterson Haddix , about a time in which drastic measures have been taken to quell overpopulation .
On Overgrown Paths is the English title of a 1949 novel by Norwegian author Knut Hamsun , and is seen as the author 's attempt at proving his soundness of mind after his sanity was called into question .
The Copper Peacock and Other Stories is a short - story collection by British writer Ruth Rendell .
Sourcery is the fifth Discworld novel by Terry Pratchett , published in 1988 .
Inspired Talks ( first published 1909 ) is book compiled from a series of lectures of Swami Vivekananda .
The Magic Item Compendium was written by Andy Collins with Eytan Bernstein , Frank Brunner , Owen K.C. Stephens , and John Snead .
The Jucklins is an 1896 novel by Opie Read .
The Law of Nations ( French : Le droit des gens ) is a work of political philosophy by Emerich de Vattel , published in 1758 .
The Colour of Blood , published in 1987 , is a political thriller by Northern Irish - Canadian novelist Brian Moore about Stephen Bem , a Cardinal in an unnamed East European country who is in conflict with the Roman Catholic Church hierarchy and finds himself caught in the middle of an escalating revolution .
All Aboard for Ararat is a 1940 allegorical novella by H. G. Wells that tells a modernized version of the story of Noah and the Flood .
Hothouses ( or Hot House Blooms , French : Serres chaudes ) ( 1889 ) is a book of symbolist poetry by Belgian Nobel Laureate Maurice Maeterlinck .
Havana Storm is a 2014 mystery novel written by international best - selling author Clive Cussler .
The Six Sacred Stones is a novel by Australian thriller author Matthew Reilly .
The Witchery of Archery , written by Maurice Thompson in 1878 , was the first book in English about hunting with a bow ever published .
The Tragedy of the Korosko ( 1898 ) is a novel by Sir Arthur Conan Doyle .
Kylie / Fashion is an official fashion photography book about the career of Australian pop singer Kylie Minogue .
What a Week Omnibus Books 4 - 6 is the second omnibus in What a Week series by Rosie Rushton .
Life Begins at Forty is a 1932 American self - help book by Walter B. Pitkin .
The Between is the first novel by writer Tananarive Due .
The Tulsi Peeth edition of the Ramcharitmanas is a critical edition of the Ramcharitmanas edited by Jagadguru Rambhadracharya and published by the Tulsi Peeth .
Boży bojownicy ( Warriors of God ) is a historical novel with fantasy elements , written by Andrzej Sapkowski .
As You Like It is a pastoral comedy by William Shakespeare believed to have been written in 1599 and first published in the First Folio , 1623 .
Curious Notions is an alternate history novel by Harry Turtledove .
Konstantin Sakaev ( Russian : Константин Сакаев ; born 13 April 1974 in Leningrad ) is a Russian chess Grandmaster ( 1993 ) , chess author and Russian champion in 1999 .
John Hopkinson , FRS , ( 27 July 1849 -- 27 August 1898 ) was a British physicist , electrical engineer , Fellow of the Royal Society and President of the IEE ( now the IET ) twice in 1890 and 1896 .
Rebati Mohan Dutta Choudhury ( 1924 - -2008 ) was a noted Assamese litterateur , Sahitya Akademi Award winner and an academician basically from Gauripur in Assam , India .
William Sully Beebe ( February 14 , 1841 -- October 12 , 1898 ) was a Union officer who received the Medal of Honor on June 30 , 1897 for his action at Cane River Crossing , Louisiana on April 23 , 1864 .
Italo Gariboldi ( 20 April 1879 -- 3 February 1970 ) was a senior officer in the Italian Royal Army ( Regio Esercito ) before and during World War II . He was awarded the Knight 's Cross of the Iron Cross by German Führer Adolf Hitler , for his leadership of Italian forces in the Battle of Stalingrad .

The Friends of Eddie Coyle is a 1973 crime film directed by Peter Yates and starring Robert Mitchum and Peter Boyle .

The King of the Kitchen is a 1918 American silent comedy film featuring Oliver Hardy .
Tropical Nights ( German : Tropennächte ) is a 1931 American German language drama film directed by Leo Mittler and starring Dita Parlo , Robert Thoeren and Fritz Greiner .
Walter Schimana ( 12 March 1898 , Troppau - 12 September 1948 , Salzburg ) was an Austrian Nazi Party and SS member , who rose to General rank ( SS - Gruppenführer und Generalleutnant der Waffen - SS und Polizei ) during World War II , and was HSSPF in occupied Greece from October 1943 .
At the outbreak of World War I Walerian Czuma joined the Piłsudski 's Polish Legions .
Joseph Lonsway ( March 17 , 1844 -- January 22 , 1925 ) was a Private in the Union Army and a Medal of Honor recipient for his actions in the American Civil War .
Upton Hays , sometimes spelled Hayes , ( March 29 , 1832 -- September 15 , 1862 ) was a colonel of the Confederate States Army during the American Civil War .
Eugène - Casimir Villatte , Comte d'Oultremont ( 14 April 1770 - 14 May 1834 ) fought in the French army during the Wars of the French Revolution and the Napoleonic Wars .
Raymond Abescat ( September 10 , 1891 in Paris -- August 15 , 2001 in Rueil - Malmaison ) was one of the last surviving veterans of World War I in France , its oldest man and the oldest veteran in France at the time of his death .
Peter Kappesser was a soldier in the United States Army who received the Medal of Honor for his actions during the American Civil War .
In part because of aid from leaders such as Awashonks , the English defeated Metacomet in King Philip 's War .
Charles W. Ray ( August 6 , 1872 - March 23 , 1959 ) was an sergeant in the United States Army and a Medal of Honor recipient for his actions in the Philippine - American War .
Brian Shul ( born 1948 ) , is a Vietnam War - era attack pilot and a retired major in the United States Air Force ( USAF ) .
Edwin Vose Sumner , Jr. ( August 16 , 1835 -- August 23 , 1912 ) was an American Union brevet brigadier general during the period of the American Civil War .
Lieutenant - Colonel Severus William Lynam Stretton ( 7 November 1783 -- 22 November 1884 ) was a British Army officer who served in the Napoleonic Wars .
Jane Whorwood , née Ryder ( 1612 -- September 1684 ) was a Royalist agent during the English Civil War .
William Henry Harman ( February 17 , 1828 -- March 2 , 1865 ) was a brigadier general in the Virginia militia and colonel in the Confederate States Army during the American Civil War ( Civil War ) .
Günther Schemmel ( 22 December 1904 -- 18 November 1990 ) was Oberstleutnant in the Wehrmacht during World War II and a recipient of the Knight 's Cross of the Iron Cross .
Hermann Graf ( 24 October 1912 -- 4 November 1988 ) was a German Luftwaffe World War II fighter ace .
James Allen Taylor ( born December 31 , 1937 ) is a retired United States Army officer and a recipient of the United States military 's highest decoration -- the Medal of Honor -- for his actions in the Vietnam War .
Achim Wunderlich ( 17 July 1912 -- 25 March 2012 ) was a highly decorated Major in the Wehrmacht during World War II , and a recipient of the Knight 's Cross of the Iron Cross .
When World War I began , Emile John Lussier claimed Medicine Hat as his home .
Henry J. Stainrook , occasionally spelled Steinrock , led a regiment of the Army of Virginia and the Army of the Potomac in the American Civil War .
William Lechmere ( 1752 -- 12 December 1815 ) was an officer of the Royal Navy who served during the American War of Independence and the French Revolutionary and Napoleonic Wars .
Hasan Tahsin Pasha ( 1845 - -1918 ) was a senior Ottoman military officer , who served in Yemen and in the First Balkan War .
Jonathan Eddy ( c. 1726 - -1804 ) served for the British in the French and Indian War and for the American Patriots in the American Revolution .
Israel Putnam ( January 7 , 1718 -- May 29 , 1790 ) was an American army general officer and Freemason , popularly known as `` Old Put '' , who fought with distinction at the Battle of Bunker Hill ( 1775 ) during the American Revolutionary War ( 1775 - -1783 ) .
Willy Bachor ( 4 May 1921 -- 20 March 2008 ) was a highly decorated Oberwachtmeister in the Wehrmacht during World War II , and a recipient of the Knight 's Cross of the Iron Cross .
Ernst Voß ( 3 November 1899 -- 11 October 1943 ) was a highly decorated Generalmajor in the Wehrmacht during World War II . Between World War I and World War II he was a Police Officer .
Captain Hilliard Brooke Bell ( 9 March 1897 -- 16 September 1960 ) was a Canadian - born World War I flying ace credited with 10 aerial victories .
Lieutenant Norman Roberts ( 1896 - -1980 ) was a British World War I flying ace credited with five aerial victories .
Arnold Meri ( 1 July 1919 -- 27 March 2009 ) was a Soviet Red Army veteran of World War II and Hero of the Soviet Union who was charged with genocide for his role in the deportation of Estonians to the inhospitable regions of the USSR .
José Santiago Albarracín 1 ( 23 July 1800 - 20 April 1869 ) was an Argentine soldier who fought on the Unitarian side in many engagements in the Argentine Civil Wars , especially in the struggles against Chacho Peñaloza .
Morgan Lewis Smith ( March 8 , 1822 -- December 29 , 1874 ) was a Union general in the American Civil War
John E. Wilkes ( May 26 , 1895 -- July 20 , 1957 ) was a vice admiral in the United States Navy , who served in World War I and World War II . In December 1941 he was appointed Commander of Submarines , Asiatic Fleet .
Charles Marquette ( 1845 - -1907 ) was a Sergeant in the United States Army and a Medal of Honor recipient for his role in the American Civil War .
Lieutenant Evander Shapard was a World War I flying ace from the United States serving in the Royal Air Force and credited with six aerial victories .
The Stevens Model 77E was the most widely used shotgun of the Vietnam War .
William Stacy ( February 15 , 1734 -- August 1802 ) was an officer of the Continental Army during the American Revolutionary War , and a pioneer to the Ohio Country .
Jean - André Valletaux ( born 23 November 1773 in Hiersac ; † 23 June 1811 Cogorderos ) was a French military commander during the French Revolutionary Wars and Napoleonic Wars , Brig - General in the Peninsular War , and Commander of the Legion of Honour .
Gerhard Fieseler ( April 15 , 1896 -- September 1 , 1987 ) was a German World War I flying ace , aerobatics champion , and aircraft designer and manufacturer .
Daniel Weisiger Adams ( May 1 , 1821 -- June 13 , 1872 ) was a lawyer and a brigadier general in the Confederate States Army during the American Civil War ( Civil War ) .
Major James Armand Meissner ( 1896 - -1936 ) was a World War I flying ace credited with eight aerial victories and awarded two Distinguished Service Crosses .
Antoine Morlot ( 5 May 1766 - 23 March 1809 ) was a French division commander during the French Revolutionary Wars and Napoleonic Wars .
The Flammenwerfer 35 , or FmW 35 ( flame thrower ) was a one - man German flamethrower used during World War II to clear out trenches and buildings .
William de la Pole , 1st Duke of Suffolk , KG ( 16 October 1396 -- 2 May 1450 ) , was an English commander in the Hundred Years ' War and Lord High Admiral of England from 1447 until 1450 .
Karl - Ernst Schroeter ( 3 December 1912 -- 23 May 1943 ) was a Korvettenkapitän with the Kriegsmarine during World War II and commander of U-121 and U-752 .
Captain Eric Douglas Cummings ( 13 April 1896 -- 27 October 1979 ) was an Australian World War I flying ace credited with nine aerial victories while flying for the Australian Flying Corps .
Augustus Louis Chetlain ( December 26 , 1824 -- March 15 , 1914 ) was an United States Army soldier -- the first man in Illinois to volunteer at the outbreak of the American Civil War .
Eberhard Wolfram ( 24 July 1882 -- 6 January 1947 ) was a Vizeadmiral with the Kriegsmarine during World War II and recipient of the Knight 's Cross of the Iron Cross ( German : Ritterkreuz des Eisernen Kreuzes ) .
USS Clover ( 1863 ) was a steam operated gunboat acquired by the Union Navy during the American Civil War .
Gottfried Heinrich Graf zu Pappenheim ( 29 May 1594 -- 7 November 1632 ) was a field marshal of the Holy Roman Empire in the Thirty Years ' War .
Giorgio Basta , Count of Huszt ( 1544 - -1607 ) was an Arbëreshë general employed by the Holy Roman Emperor Rudolf II to command Habsburg forces in the Long War of 1591 - -1606 .
Maurice Graham English was a World War I Irish aviator who was shot down by German flying ace Hans Goerth .
Lieutenant General Alan Shapley ( February 9 , 1903 - May 13 , 1973 ) was a United States Marine Corps officer who survived the sinking of the USS Arizona during the World War II Attack on Pearl Harbor , and went on to serve with distinction in the Pacific Theater and later in the Korean War .
Luis González de Ubieta y González del Campillo ( 1899 -- 1950 ) was an admiral of the Spanish Republican Navy during the Spanish Civil War .
Fred Godfrey ( 17 September 1880 -- 22 February 1953 ) was the pen name of Llewellyn Williams , a World War I songwriter .
Colonel Sir William Howe De Lancey KCB ( 1778 -- 26 June 1815 ) was an officer in the British Army during the Napoleonic Wars .
Lloyd Tilghman ( January 26 , 1816 -- May 16 , 1863 ) was a Confederate general in the American Civil War .
Anastasios Karatasos ( Greek : Αναστάσιος Καρατάσος ; 1764 -- 21 January 1830 ) was a Greek military commander during the Greek War of Independence was born in the village of Dovras ( Δοβράς or Δορβρά ) , Imathia and is considered to be the most important revolutionary from Macedonia .
Major - General Daniel Hoghton ( 27 August 1770 -- 16 May 1811 ) was a talented and experienced British Army officer who served during the Napoleonic Wars with distinction until his death during combat with the French at the Battle of Albuera in the Peninsula War .
Edward R. Hanford ( 1845 - -1890 ) was a private in the 2nd U.S. Cavalry , Company H , during the American Civil War .
85 Ceti is an older Flamsteed designation for a star that is now within the borders of the northern constellation of Aries , the ram .
HD 220035 is variable star in the equatorial constellation of Aquarius .
HD 126128/9 is a triple star in the northern constellation of Boötes .
42 Cancri ( 42 Cnc or HD 73785 ) is a star in the constellation Cancer .
EQ Virginis is a flare star in the constellation of Virgo .
HD 143361 b is an extrasolar planet located approximately 194 light - years away in the constellation of Norma , orbiting the 9th magnitude G - type main sequence star HD 143361 .
11 Comae Berenices b , ( 11 Com b ) is an extrasolar planet orbiting the star 11 Comae Berenices , approximately 360.79lys away in the constellation of Coma Berenices .
11 Ursae Minoris b is an extrasolar planet which orbits the K - type giant star 11 Ursae Minoris , located approximately 390 light years away in the constellation Ursa Minor .
V838 Monocerotis ( V838 Mon ) is a red variable star in the constellation Monoceros about 20,000 light years ( 6 kpc ) from the Sun . The previously unknown star was observed in early 2002 experiencing a major outburst , and was possibly one of the largest known stars for a short period following the outburst .
Eta Capricorni ( η Cap , η Capricorni ) is a binary star in the constellation Capricornus .
NGC 55 is a Magellanic type barred spiral galaxy located about 7 million light - years away in the constellation Sculptor .

NGC 6818 ( also known as Little Gem Nebula ) is a planetary nebula located in the constellation of Sagittarius .

19 Monocerotis ( 19 Mon ) is a star in the constellation Monoceros .

NGC 2915 is a blue dwarf galaxy located 12 million light - years away in the southern constellation Chamaeleon , right on the edge of the Local Group .
Kappa Scorpii ( κ Sco , κ Scorpii ) is a binary star system in the southern constellation of Scorpius .
